Title: Defeasible Reasoning with Legal Rules in a Deontic Logic based on Preferences  
Author: Lamber Royakkers Frank Dignum 
Address: P.O.box 90153, 5000 LE Tilburg  P.O.box 513, 5600 MB Eindhoven  
Affiliation: Dept. of Legal Informatics Tilburg University  Dept. of Mathematics and Computer Science Eindhoven University of Technology  
Abstract: Over the last few years several defeasible deontic reasoning formalisms have been developed to solve the problem of deontic inconsistency. However, these formalisms are unable to deal with some very common forms of deontic reasoning since, e.g., their expressiveness is restricted. In this paper, which is based on Royakkers and Dignum (1996), we will establish a priority hierarchy of legal rules to solve the problem of deontic conflicts, and we will present a mechanism to reason about nonmonotonicity of legal rules over the priority hierarchy. The theory presented here, based on default logic, and being a modification and extension of Prakken's argumentation framework, adequately deals with some shortcomings of other defeasible deontic reasoning approaches. 
